    "summary": "Scipio Africanus (236–183 BC) was Rome's greatest general of the Second Punic War and the man who defeated [[event:1054|Hannibal's Invasion of Italy]]'s Hannibal at the Battle of Zama (202 BC), ending the war that had brought Rome to the edge of catastrophe. Appointed commander in Spain at age 25 after the deaths of his father and uncle, he revolutionized Roman tactics by adopting and improving on the flexible Hellenistic maniple system, introducing the use of cavalry as a decisive arm, and incorporating psychological warfare.\n\nHis conquest of New Carthage (Cartagena) in Spain in 209 BC in a single daring assault, and his victory at Ilipa (206 BC), drove Carthage from Spain. He then took the war to Africa, threatening Carthage itself and forcing the recall of Hannibal. At Zama, he neutralized Hannibal's elephant corps and used superior cavalry coordination to encircle the Carthaginian army — a reversal of Hannibal's own tactics at Cannae. Scipio's victory established Rome's Mediterranean supremacy, but his popularity made political enemies; he was prosecuted late in life by Cato the Elder and died in voluntary exile.",
